@node MAIN "PetMate for AmigaOS - User Guide"

@{b}PetMate for AmigaOS 3.x@{ub}
@{b}PETSCII Art Editor@{ub}

                        User Manual

  PetMate is a PETSCII art editor for AmigaOS 3.x, ported from the
  original open-source Petmate project. It lets you create and edit
  character-based artwork using the Commodore 64 PETSCII character
  set, with export to multiple formats including native C64 programs.

  @{" Introduction        " link INTRO}       What is PetMate?
  @{" Requirements        " link REQUIRE}     Minimum system requirements
  @{" Interface Overview  " link INTERFACE}   The main window layout
  @{" Drawing Tools       " link TOOLS}       The six drawing modes
  @{" Color Palettes      " link PALETTES}    C64 color palette options
  @{" Brush Operations    " link BRUSH}       Lasso, transform, and use
  @{" Screen Management   " link SCREENS}     Working with multiple screens
  @{" Generate Menu       " link GENERATE}    Procedural content generation
  @{" Menus Reference     " link MENUS}       Complete menu reference
  @{" Keyboard Shortcuts  " link KEYS}        All keyboard shortcuts
  @{" Export Formats      " link EXPORT}      Exporting your artwork
  @{" Import              " link IMPORT}      Importing images
  @{" File Format         " link FORMAT}      The .petmate project format
  @{" Credits             " link CREDITS}     Authors and licenses

@endnode


@node INTRO "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  PetMate is a PETSCII art editor running natively on AmigaOS 3.x.
  PETSCII (PET Standard Code of Information Interchange) is the
  character set used by Commodore 8-bit computers, most famously
  the Commodore 64.

  The original Petmate was written in TypeScript/React for desktop
  operating systems. This Amiga port is written in C89 using the
  BOOPSI and ReAction GUI toolkits native to AmigaOS.

  @{b}Features at a glance:@{ub}

    - Six drawing tools: Draw, Colorize, CharDraw, Brush, Text, Reverse Draw
    - Full 16-color C64 palette with four palette variants
    - Lasso brush with rotate and mirror transforms
    - Up to 64 screens per project
    - Undo / Redo
    - Procedural generation: Random Brush, Magic Line, Tron Lines
    - Export to IFF ILBM, GIF, C64 BASIC, ASM, and PRG files
    - Import images and convert them to PETSCII
    - Project files in .petmate JSON format (cross-platform)

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node REQUIRE "Requirements"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

  @{b}Minimum configuration:@{ub}

    CPU       Motorola 68020 or better
    OS        AmigaOS 3.9

  @{b}Recommended configuration:@{ub}

    OS        AmigaOS 3.2.3 or later

  AmigaOS 3.2.3 provides better system library support and is the
  recommended platform for the best experience. The application
  runs on OS 3.9 but some system features may be limited.

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node INTERFACE "Interface Overview"

@{b}Interface Overview@{ub}

  The main window is divided into several areas:

  @{b}Canvas (center)@{ub}
    The main editing area showing the current screen. Each cell
    displays a PETSCII character with its foreground color on the
    current background color. Click or drag to draw.

  @{b}Left Toolbar@{ub}
    Vertical strip of tool buttons along the left edge:

      Draw         - Select the Draw tool (F1)
      Colorize     - Select the Colorize tool (F2)
      CharDraw     - Select the CharDraw tool (F3)
      Brush        - Select the Lasso Brush tool (F4)
      Text         - Select the Text tool (F5)
      Reverse Draw - Select the Reverse Draw tool (F6)
      Undo         - Undo last change
      Redo      - Redo last undone change
      Clear     - Clear the current screen

  @{b}Color Picker@{ub}
    Displays all 16 C64 colors from the active palette. Click a
    color to select it as the active foreground color. A separate
    indicator shows the current background color.

  @{b}Character Selector@{ub}
    A 16x16 grid showing all 256 PETSCII characters from the
    active charset (upper or lower). Click a character to select
    it as the active drawing character.

  @{b}Screen Carousel@{ub}
    A vertical strip of thumbnail previews, one per screen in the
    project. Click a thumbnail to switch to that screen. The
    current screen is highlighted.

  @{b}Status Bar@{ub}
    Displays feedback messages and operation status at the bottom
    of the window.

  @{b}Grid Overlay@{ub}
    An optional pixel grid can be toggled on/off to help with
    precise character placement (View menu or G key).

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node TOOLS "Drawing Tools"

@{b}Drawing Tools@{ub}

  PetMate has six drawing tools selected via the Edit menu or
  function keys. The active tool determines what happens when you
  click or drag on the canvas.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Draw  (F1)@{ub}

    The standard drawing tool. Clicking a canvas cell places the
    currently selected character AND applies the currently selected
    foreground color. Both character and color are changed.

    This is the most commonly used tool for building PETSCII art
    from scratch.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Colorize  (F2)@{ub}

    Applies the current foreground color to cells without changing
    the character already in those cells. Use this to repaint
    areas of the canvas with a different color while preserving
    the characters.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}CharDraw  (F3)@{ub}

    Places the currently selected character without changing the
    existing color of the cell. The character is updated but the
    foreground color of each cell is kept. Useful for laying out
    structure while preserving a color scheme.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Lasso Brush  (F4)@{ub}

    Click and drag to select a rectangular region of the canvas.
    The selection becomes the active @{"brush" link BRUSH}. Once a brush is
    captured, clicking elsewhere on the canvas stamps a copy of
    the brush at that position.

    While a brush is active, the Brush menu becomes available,
    offering flip and rotate transforms.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Text  (F5)@{ub}

    Places the cursor on the canvas and allows direct keyboard
    text entry. Characters typed are placed using the current
    foreground color. The cursor advances automatically after
    each character.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Reverse Draw  (F6)@{ub}

    Click and drag to select a rectangular region of the canvas.
    When the mouse button is released, the foreground and
    background colors of every cell inside the selection are
    swapped. The characters in those cells are not changed.

    This is useful for quickly inverting a region to create
    highlighted or selected-looking areas in your PETSCII art.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{" Brush Operations " link BRUSH}
  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node BRUSH "Brush Operations"

@{b}Brush Operations@{ub}

  A brush is a rectangular block of PETSCII cells captured from
  the canvas using the Lasso Brush tool (F4). It remembers both
  the characters and the colors of the captured region.

  @{b}Capturing a Brush@{ub}

    1. Select the Lasso Brush tool (F4 or Edit > Draw 4).
    2. Click and drag on the canvas to draw a selection rectangle.
    3. Release the mouse button. The selected area is now the
       active brush.

  @{b}Stamping a Brush@{ub}

    With an active brush, click anywhere on the canvas to stamp
    a copy of the brush at that position. The brush respects the
    active drawing tool:

      Draw mode     - places characters AND colors from brush
      Colorize mode - places colors only from brush
      CharDraw mode - places characters only from brush

  @{b}Brush Transforms@{ub}

    Once a brush is captured the Brush menu becomes enabled.
    The following transforms are available:

      @{b}Flip X@{ub}       Mirror the brush horizontally (left becomes right)
      @{b}Flip Y@{ub}       Mirror the brush vertically (top becomes bottom)
      @{b}Rotate 90 CW@{ub}  Rotate the brush 90 degrees clockwise
      @{b}Rotate 180@{ub}   Rotate the brush 180 degrees
      @{b}Rotate 90 CCW@{ub} Rotate the brush 90 degrees counter-clockwise

    Note: rotations also remap characters to their correct
    orientation equivalents (e.g. a corner piece facing one
    direction is swapped for the matching corner facing the
    rotated direction).

  @{b}Random Brush Fill@{ub}

    Generate > Random Brush fills the entire screen with randomly
    selected cells from the active brush. If no brush is active,
    diagonal half-block characters are used instead. The fill
    respects the current drawing tool mode.

  @{" Drawing Tools    " link TOOLS}
  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node PALETTES "Color Palettes"

@{b}Color Palettes@{ub}

  The C64 has a fixed set of 16 colors. Different emulators and
  hardware revisions render these colors slightly differently.
  PetMate offers four palette variants that correspond to popular
  reference standards.

  Select a palette from the Palette menu. The active palette is
  shown with a checkmark.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Petmate@{ub}  (default)

    The default palette used by the original Petmate editor.
    A well-balanced general-purpose C64 palette.

  @{b}Colodore@{ub}

    The Colodore palette, widely regarded as a physically accurate
    model of the C64's VIC-II color output based on measurement.

  @{b}Pepto@{ub}

    The Pepto palette, another measurement-based palette by Tobias
    Gubber, commonly used as a reference in emulation.

  @{b}VICE@{ub}

    The palette used by the VICE Commodore emulator.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}The 16 C64 Colors@{ub}

    Index  Name
    -----  ----------
      0    Black
      1    White
      2    Red
      3    Cyan
      4    Purple
      5    Green
      6    Blue
      7    Yellow
      8    Orange
      9    Brown
     10    Light Red
     11    Dark Grey
     12    Grey
     13    Light Green
     14    Light Blue
     15    Light Grey

  Each character cell has an independent foreground color. The
  background color and border color are shared across the screen.

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node SCREENS "Screen Management"

@{b}Screen Management@{ub}

  A PetMate project can contain up to 64 screens. Each screen is
  an independent 40x25 character canvas with its own background
  color, border color, and character set selection.

  Screens are managed from the Screen menu and the on-screen
  carousel.

  @{b}Navigating Screens@{ub}

    Previous Screen   [ key or Screen > Previous Screen
    Next Screen       ] key or Screen > Next Screen

    Clicking a thumbnail in the screen carousel also navigates
    directly to that screen.

  @{b}Adding and Removing Screens@{ub}

    Add Screen      Appends a new blank screen after the current one.
    Clone Screen    Appends a copy of the current screen.
    Remove Screen   Deletes the current screen. Cannot remove the
                    last remaining screen in a project.

  @{b}Copy and Paste Screens@{ub}

    Edit > Copy Screen   Copies the entire current screen to an
                         internal clipboard.
    Edit > Paste Screen  Replaces the current screen with the
                         clipboard contents.

  @{b}Shifting Screen Content@{ub}

    The content of the canvas can be shifted one character at a
    time in any direction. Cells that move off one edge wrap
    around to the opposite edge.

    Edit > Shift Left
    Edit > Shift Right
    Edit > Shift Up
    Edit > Shift Down

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node GENERATE "Generate Menu"

@{b}Generate Menu@{ub}

  The Generate menu provides three procedural content generators
  that fill the current screen with algorithmically created
  patterns. They are useful as starting points for artwork or to
  quickly fill backgrounds.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Random Brush@{ub}

    Fills the entire screen with randomly selected cells drawn
    from the active brush. The fill mode follows the active tool:

      Draw      - places random characters AND colors from brush
      Colorize  - places random colors only from brush
      CharDraw  - places random characters only from brush

    If no brush is captured, the fill uses a random selection of
    diagonal half-block characters.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Magic Line@{ub}

    Draws continuous worm-like paths across the screen using
    PETSCII line-drawing characters. Three algorithms are cycled
    through on successive invocations:

      @{b}Algorithm A - Random Worm@{ub}
        A worm walks across the screen, changing direction
        approximately 20% of the time. Creates flowing, organic
        line traces.

      @{b}Algorithm B - Reconnecting Worm@{ub}
        Similar to Algorithm A but with a homing bias: 40% of
        steps are influenced toward the starting position. Creates
        closed loops and figure-of-eight patterns.

      @{b}Algorithm C - Fractal Quad-Cross@{ub}
        A recursive fractal algorithm that generates symmetric
        cross and branching patterns.

    Junction characters are automatically selected to correctly
    represent corners, T-junctions, and straight segments.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Tron Lines@{ub}

    Inspired by the light cycles from the film Tron. Four
    players begin at random positions on the screen and travel
    in straight lines, turning 90 degrees at random intervals
    of 2 to 7 steps. A player is eliminated when it has no
    free cells to move into.

    Crossing paths automatically generate the correct junction
    characters where lines intersect.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


