@node EXPORT "Export Formats"

@{b}Export Formats@{ub}

  PetMate can export the current screen to several formats via
  Project > Export As. A file requester will ask for the output
  file path and name.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}IFF ILBM  (.ilbm)@{ub}

    Exports as an Amiga IFF ILBM image file with 4 bitplanes
    (16 colors). The CMAP chunk contains the active palette
    colors. The image is 320x200 pixels (or 384x272 with the
    optional C64 border). This format can be opened directly by
    most Amiga image viewers and paint programs.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}GIF  (.gif)@{ub}

    Exports as a GIF87a image with a 16-color global color map
    matching the active palette. The image is 320x200 pixels
    (or 384x272 with the C64 border). Suitable for sharing on
    modern systems.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}BASIC  (.bas)@{ub}

    Exports a BASIC source text file containing DATA statements
    with the screen codes and color values for each row of the
    screen. The file can be loaded into a C64 and used in a
    BASIC program with POKE statements to display the image.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}ASM  (.asm)@{ub}

    Exports an ACME assembler source file with @{b}!byte@{ub} directives
    and labels. The data is laid out as screen character data
    and color RAM data, ready for inclusion in a 6510 assembly
    project.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}PRG BASIC  (.prg)@{ub}

    Exports a ready-to-run Commodore 64 program file. The PRG
    contains a minimal BASIC stub (SYS) that jumps to machine
    code which copies the screen and color data to the C64
    display memory, then stops. Load and RUN it on a real C64
    or in an emulator.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}PRG ASM  (.prg)@{ub}

    Exports a ready-to-run Commodore 64 program file with a
    pure machine code loader (no BASIC). The PRG copies the
    screen and color RAM data to the C64 display memory.

  ---------------------------------------------------------------

  @{b}Image dimensions@{ub}

    Standard:  320 x 200 pixels  (40 x 25 characters at 8x8)
    Bordered:  384 x 272 pixels  (with 8-pixel C64 border strips)

  @{" Import          " link IMPORT}
  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node IMPORT "Import"

@{b}Import@{ub}

  PetMate can import an existing image and automatically convert
  it to a PETSCII representation.

  @{b}Project > Import > Image@{ub}

    Opens a file requester. Select an image file to import.

    @{b}Supported image formats:@{ub}
      PNG, GIF, BMP, IFF, ILBM, JPG, JPEG

    The importer uses the Amiga picture.datatype system to load
    the image. This requires datatypes.library version 40 or
    higher (AmigaOS 3.5 or later, or an equivalent third-party
    datatype installation).

    @{b}Supported input dimensions:@{ub}
      320 x 200  (borderless C64 screen)
      384 x 272  (C64 screen with 8-pixel border)

    @{b}Conversion process:@{ub}

      1. The image is loaded via picture.datatype.
      2. The image is quantised to the 16-color C64 palette.
      3. All 16 possible background colors are tried in turn to
         find the combination that best reproduces the original
         image in PETSCII.
      4. The resulting 40x25 screen is inserted as the current
         screen.

    The quality of the conversion depends strongly on whether
    the source image was originally created as PETSCII art or
    is a screenshot of C64 output. Photographic images will
    produce approximate results.

  @{" Export Formats  " link EXPORT}
  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


@node FORMAT "File Format"

@{b}File Format@{ub}

  PetMate projects are saved as @{b}.petmate@{ub} files. These are plain
  JSON text files compatible with the original Petmate editor on
  Windows, macOS, and Linux.

  @{b}Contents of a .petmate file:@{ub}

    - All screens in the project (up to 64)
    - For each screen: the character code and color for every
      cell, plus background color, border color, and charset
    - The active palette selection
    - Project metadata

  @{b}Screen dimensions:@{ub}

    The default screen size is 40 x 25 characters (the standard
    C64 text screen). The settings window allows other dimensions
    up to 80 x 50 characters for non-standard use.

  Because the format is plain JSON it can be inspected and edited
  with any text editor, and projects created on any platform can
  be opened on the Amiga without conversion.

  @{" Back to Contents " link MAIN}

@endnode


